The paper focuses on preserving privacy in social network topologies, which falls under the category of social networks (cs.SOC). The paper also proposes an algorithm for anonymizing links, which involves community detection (cs.SI) and has implications for security and privacy (cs.CR). The paper also discusses metrics for quantifying privacy and utility, which could fall under databases (cs.DB) or cybersecurity (cs.CYBER).
